---
description: All code (TS/JS/JSX/GQL and similar) must be vertically readable — no crammed dense one-liners.
alwaysApply: true
---

# Readable code layout

Code must expose its structure at a glance. Prefer vertical clarity over saving lines. Do not cram unrelated members, arguments, fields, or clauses onto one line when readability suffers.

Applies to every platform and language in this workspace: `backend/`, `website/`, `cpanel/`, shared `docs/` examples, and generated mirrors when you touch them.

## Required (all languages)

- **Two or more siblings** (properties, arguments, fields, variables, imports of the same group) → one per line with normal indentation.
- **Nested structures** (`query`, `params`, config blocks, SDL field groups, selection sets) → nested block; one member per line.
- **Contract maps** (`MPagesRoutes`, `PagesRoutes`, `BreadcrumbMeta`, route tables, enum maps) → always multi-line shapes; bare `{}` may stay on one line.
- **Long generics or unions** → named `type` alias instead of splitting `Record<...>` / `Pick<...>` across awkward lines.
- **Logical sections** → blank line between unrelated groups (imports vs code, SDL sections, hook blocks).

## TypeScript / JavaScript

- Object types, literals, destructuring, and `return` objects with 2+ keys → multi-line.
- Function calls with 2+ named arguments or 3+ positional arguments → break across lines.
- Chained calls (`.map().filter().reduce()`, fluent builders) → break when the chain is hard to scan; one meaningful step per line.
- JSX: 2+ props on a component → one prop per line unless the element is a trivial leaf with two short props.
- Import lists: do not pack many symbols on one line; group and break by source module.

Forbidden:

```ts
CustomerSettings: {
    id?: string;
};

nav.push("CustomerSettings", {
    id,
});
const x = useMemo(() => ({ a, b, c, d }), [a, b, c, d]);
```

Good:

```ts
CustomerSettings: {
    id?: string;
};

nav.push("CustomerSettings", {
    id,
});
```

## GraphQL SDL (`.graphql`)

- One field, argument, or directive per line.
- Group related fields with comments and blank lines (`# info`, `# relations`, `# pagination`) — match existing schema style.
- Type definitions, `implements`, and interfaces: members listed vertically, not inline.
- Input types and argument lists: one argument per line.

Forbidden:

```graphql
type _Foo { id: ID! name: String status: _Status customer: _Customer notifications: [_Notification] }
query customers($filter: _CustomerFilter, $sort: _CustomerSort) { customers(filter: $filter, sort: $sort) { id name } }
```

Good:

```graphql
type _Foo {
    id: ID!
    name: String
    status: _Status
    customer: _Customer
    notifications: [_Notification]
}

query customers($filter: _CustomerFilter, $sort: _CustomerSort) {
    customers(filter: $filter, sort: $sort) {
        id
        name
    }
}
```

## GraphQL operations (client `.graphql` / embedded query strings)

- Selection sets: one field per line; nested selections indented.
- Variables and arguments: one per line when there are 2+.
- Fragments and operation names stay on their own lines.

Forbidden:

```graphql
query LoadCustomer($id: ID!) { customer(id: $id) { id name email status { value label } } }
```

Good:

```graphql
query LoadCustomer($id: ID!) {
    customer(id: $id) {
        id
        name
        email
        status {
            value
            label
        }
    }
}
```

## Allowed compact forms

- Empty shape: `Login: {}`
- Single-member shape when the name already explains it and the value is short (when unsure, expand).
- One-line `return` only when the object or expression has a **single** short element.
- Single short statement with no nested structure (e.g. `const id = params.id;`).

## Forbidden everywhere

- “Writer style” dense one-liners that hide structure to save vertical space.
- Stacking unrelated fields, args, or clauses on one line.
- Minified or golfed style in hand-written source (not build output).
